                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/2275</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-02-28T17:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 28, 1916, 5 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 7.20 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3872. <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward Grey</persName> has again informed
                    me that he expects the English and French answer to our long note on shipping to
                    be <pb facs="0638" n="352" xml:id="pg_352"/> ready next week. The English answer
                    is now before the Cabinet and he is urging the French to haste. He expresses
                    regret at the long time consumed and wishes me to assure you that he is
                    hastening the answer as urgently as possible.</p>
                <closer>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
